<personal-details:content>French translator (EN/IT–FR) and interpreter (IT–FR) based in Rome, with over 40 years of professional experience. In parallel with my translation practice, I pursue independent research focusing on machine translation and artificial intelligence. Through my studies I have brought to light the invention of Federico Pucci, an early and overlooked pioneer whose theoretical contributions anticipated both rule-based machine translation and interlingua systems. My publications include hundreds of blog posts and scholarly articles in English, French, and Italian, examining the intersections of language, technology, and history. One of my recent works, The Forgotten Code: Validating a Century-Old Translation System with AI (arXiv:2509.02506), reflects my ongoing interest in revisiting historical approaches to translation through the lens of modern AI.</personal-details:content>
</person:biography>
